{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17644644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17644644"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:06:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:06:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18049"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18049","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18049"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.5,0.04,0.04,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10763"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73382"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10763"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18049"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58848"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7381"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25109"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25112"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/73382"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after a high-speed motor vehicle accident. He complains of severe pain in his right shoulder and difficulty moving his arm. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is tenderness over the right scapular region, and he has limited range of motion in the right shoulder. An X-ray of the shoulder is performed, revealing a fracture.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following parts of the scapula is most likely to be fractured in this scenario?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Subscapular fossa","Acromion","Coracoid process","Glenoid cavity","Scapular spine"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn the context of a high-energy trauma such as a motor vehicle accident, the \u003Cstrong\u003Eacromion\u003C/strong\u003E and the body of the scapula are the most commonly fractured parts. The acromion is a bony projection on the scapula that forms the highest point of the shoulder and is susceptible to direct impact injuries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esubscapular fossa\u003C/strong\u003E is a concave surface on the anterior aspect of the scapula and is less commonly fractured compared to the acromion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecoracoid process\u003C/strong\u003E is a small hook-like structure on the scapula and fractures here are less common, often associated with other shoulder injuries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eglenoid cavity\u003C/strong\u003E is the part of the scapula that articulates with the head of the humerus to form the shoulder joint. Fractures of the glenoid are less common and usually occur with dislocations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Escapular spine\u003C/strong\u003E is a prominent ridge running across the posterior surface of the scapula. While it can be fractured, it is less commonly involved than the acromion in high-energy trauma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The acromion and the body of the scapula are the most commonly fractured parts of the scapula.","Scapular fractures often result from high-energy trauma and may be associated with other injuries.","Understanding the anatomy of the scapula is crucial for diagnosing and managing scapular fractures."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17.","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618.","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). (2015). Oxford textbook of musculoskeletal medicine. Oxford University Press.","McCausland C, Sawyer E, Eovaldi BJ, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder Muscles. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30521257.","Paulsen, F., \u0026 Waschke, J. (Eds.). (2023). Sobotta Atlas of Anatomy, Vol. 1, English/Latin: General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System (Vol. 1). Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58848"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18049"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58848"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-23T12:55:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-23T12:56:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10763"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"73382"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"d